... I think the reason to newtype would be exactly what I described above. To show/eq the PeanoF, the TH derived Show1, Eq1 instance is needed. "*F" has no option but do a type class jump to r (itself). It becomes understandable that those Eq1 are costly. newtype of a fixed type can infer(/have) the proper instances that do not require self-type class jump, so they become internally recursive, to which even some transformations probably can be applied. To say, mere putting newtype over Fix .. probably should lead to faster type class instances code.
Commented on #321 Trying to understand the `NExprF` typeclass deriving mechanics

Lately I walked the deriving list in Expr, and yes, most of what is - indeed requires TH deriving.
It seems that for some type classes for recursion schemes data types the metaprogramming space is needed. Even for such simple thing as Peano numbers ((Succ (Succ Nil))``) HOF versions of basic type classes can not bederivingor standalone deriving, or strategized. (still currently) A lift of the deriving procedure into TH space is required to derive them, for Peano for example that would beShow1,Eq1`. I can not point towards moment why it is the case, but it is a case. I guess it is because of recursive data type nature that into the TH space arrives solved. Indeed that particularly backward compatibility package deriving-compat has them (forward thinking instances) is pretty surprising. This TH deriving functionality probably belongs to be a separate package. If not to be included into TH itself. As I found it to be extremely useful.
Regarding that NExpr is a type synonym - it is still. (I search for it) so far (strangely enough) there was no strong reason to make such core type as NExpr the newtype .
